They are NOT covered by the MIT license above. Both platforms intentionally
ship LGPL builds (never GPL builds) so a closed-source application may link
them, provided the application honors the LGPL terms.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
iOS / tvOS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Component:   mpv + FFmpeg, via MPVKit
Product:     "MPVKit" (LGPL v3.0) — NOT "MPVKit-GPL"
FFmpeg:      built WITHOUT --enable-gpl (LGPL configuration)
Source:      https://github.com/mpvkit/MPVKit  (see its release tags for the
             exact mpv / FFmpeg versions bundled by the pinned MPVKit release)
License:     GNU LGPL v3.0

  mpv:    https://github.com/mpv-player/mpv      (LGPL v2.1+)
  FFmpeg: https://ffmpeg.org/                    (LGPL v2.1+, version3 enabled)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Android
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Component:   mpv + FFmpeg, built as a custom LGPL libmpv AAR
mpv:         configured with --enable-lgpl
FFmpeg:      configured WITHOUT --enable-gpl, using --enable-version3 (LGPL v3)
Build:       the public build scripts used to produce the AAR live in this
             repository under android/libmpv-build/. They are derived from
             https://github.com/jarnedemeulemeester/libmpv-android
License:     GNU LGPL v3.0

  NOTE: The prebuilt Maven artifact dev.jdtech.mpv:libmpv:* is a GPL build and
  is deliberately NOT used by this package.

